Certainly! Here's a simple example of a login form using PHP. It will include:

- An HTML form for user input
- PHP code to process the login, check credentials (for demonstration, credentials are hard-coded)

---

### 1. Create an HTML form (`login.html`):

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <title>Login</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>Login</h2>
    <form action="login.php" method="post">
        <label for="username">Username:</label>
        <input type="text" id="username" name="username" required />
        <br />

        <label for="password">Password:</label>
        <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required />
        <br />

        <input type="submit" value="Login" />
    </form>
</body>
</html>
```

---

### 2. Create the PHP login processing script (`login.php`):

```php
<?php
// Sample hard-coded user credentials (In real scenarios, use a database)
$valid_username = "admin";
$valid_password = "password123";

// Start the session
session_start();

// Check if form data is submitted
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] == 'POST') {
    // Retrieve submitted username and password
    $username = $_POST['username'];
    $password = $_POST['password'];

    // Validate credentials
    if ($username === $valid_username && $password === $valid_password) {
        // Store login status in session
        $_SESSION['loggedin'] = true;
        $_SESSION['username'] = $username;

        // Redirect to a protected page
        header("Location: welcome.php");
        exit();
    } else {
        // Invalid credentials
        echo "Invalid username or password. Please try again.";
    }
}
?>
```

---

### 3. Create a welcome page (`welcome.php`) for logged-in users:

```php
<?php
session_start();

// Check login status
if (!isset($_SESSION['loggedin']) || $_SESSION['loggedin'] !== true) {
    header("Location: login.html");
    exit();
}
?>

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <title>Welcome</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>Welcome, <?php echo htmlspecialchars($_SESSION['username']); ?>!</h2>
    <p>You are logged in.</p>
    <a href="logout.php">Logout</a>
</body>
</html>
```

---

### 4. Create a logout script (`logout.php`):

```php
<?php
session_start();
session_destroy();
header("Location: login.html");
exit();
?>
```

---

### Summary:
- `login.html` has the form to enter username/password.
- `login.php` processes login credentials.
- `welcome.php` is the protected page.
- `logout.php` logs out the user.

---

**Note:** Never store passwords in plain text or hard-coded in production. Always hash passwords and use a database. This example is for educational purposes only.

